(82, 1, '2013-02-21 20:10:05', '2013-02-21 20:10:05', '<a href="http://ayalaferndalehomes-ferndale168.rhcloud.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/Chinese-New-Year.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-75" alt="Chinese-New-Year" src="http://ayalaferndalehomes-ferndale168.rhcloud.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/Chinese-New-Year.jpg" width="1750" height="1166" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<div>For Pinoys, New Year''s Eve feasts are almost always a test. Resolutions to eat in moderation dissolve at the stroke of midnight, when the whole family indulges in dishes like ham, chicken, and of course, lechon.</div>\r\n<div></div>\r\n<div>For those trying to eat less meat, it''s almost impossible to survive such occasions. A few years ago, I found myself with only bread to eat for Christmas dinner, because my family forgot I was vegetarian. I eventually included seafood in my diet, but big celebrations are still a challenge.</div>\r\n<div></div>\r\n<div>When it comes to the Chinese New Year, the feast is also abundant, but the dishes are noticeably healthier. This is, of course, good news for pescetarians, but even meat eaters can appreciate a feast that won''t make you worry too much about your cholesterol after.</div>', 'Kung Hei Fat Choi', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '72-revision-3', '', '', '2013-02-21 20:10:05', '2013-02-21 20:10:05', '', 72, 'http://ayalaferndalehomes-ferndale168.rhcloud.com/?p=82', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
